      "side": 1,
      "message": "IMHO we need to be clearer, in both the text and examples, that this function will return true for non-error yet incomplete values like `string`.\n\nI also still don\u0027t like this name. The spec doesn\u0027t define what a \"valid value\" is, and \"valid\" is a general term that can too easily be misunderstood. I see a few alternatives:\n\n1) `succeeds`, implying \"it evaluates without an error\"\n2) `validates`, like the previous option, but closer to `cue vet` and `cue.Value.Validate`\n3) with a negated result, `finalError` or `isError`, although I don\u0027t like the negated version as much\n\nI\u0027d personally go for option 2, or if not, option 1. I see either as better than \"is valid\".",
      "revId": "7a20952ac04e48723f9ec03769eee632cc3f5be4",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
